title: azure-identity prototype
user: @{login=chlowell; id=10964656; node_id=MDQ6VXNlcjEwOTY0NjU2; avatar_url=https://avatars0.githubusercontent.com/u/10964656?v=4; gravatar_id=; url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell; html_url=https://github.com/chlowell; followers_url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell/followers; following_url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell/following{/other_user}; gists_url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell/gists{/gist_id}; starred_url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell/starred{/owner}{/repo}; subscriptions_url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell/subscriptions; organizations_url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell/orgs; repos_url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell/repos; events_url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell/events{/privacy}; received_events_url=https://api.github.com/users/chlowell/received_events; type=User; site_admin=False}
body:
Deviations from the original design sketch:
 - Removed `get_credentials` layer. Calling `provider.get_credential(scopes).get_token(scopes)` seems unnecessary when the provider could simply provide the token directly, i.e. the credential seems to have little value independent of the token.
 - Replaced credential ABC with a Protocol.
 - Favored `TokenProvider` over `CredentialProvider` in naming.

Note that this code doesn't work because it relies on in-flight `azure-core` code, and that there will be equivalent async code in the final package.

title: add support got global settings
user: @{login=bryevdv; id=1078448; node_id=MDQ6VXNlcjEwNzg0NDg=; avatar_url=https://avatars3.githubusercontent.com/u/1078448?v=4; gravatar_id=; url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv; html_url=https://github.com/bryevdv; followers_url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv/followers; following_url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv/following{/other_user}; gists_url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv/gists{/gist_id}; starred_url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv/starred{/owner}{/repo}; subscriptions_url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv/subscriptions; organizations_url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv/orgs; repos_url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv/repos; events_url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv/events{/privacy}; received_events_url=https://api.github.com/users/bryevdv/received_events; type=User; site_admin=False}
body:
cc @johanste @annatisch 

* closes #5126 

Absent other considerations, I created a tool I would personally use in a project. A few notes:

* As it stands, `None` is not a valid value for "immediate" values (it signals the absence of a value). I  considered using `Unset` for this purpose, but that places a burden on all users of this class, and absent optional function arguments are regularly denoted by `None` anyway.

* There's an asymmetry between user-setting a value, and getting the computed value:

    ```
    settings.log_level = logging.DEBUG  # set, assignmemt

    level = settings.log_level(...)  # get, function
    ```
    This is necessitated by having `settings` arbitrate case 4) itself. It's well within my comfort zone  (especially since I suspect case 3) is not common), but thoughts welcome. 

* With this descriptor approach, it would be simple to add an argument to `PrioritizedSetting` to add a `__doc__` for the attributes. 

* Do we want to allow fail-through if, e.g. a system hook raises an exception or otherwise does not succeed?

user: @{login=samvaity; id=16845631; node_id=MDQ6VXNlcjE2ODQ1NjMx; avatar_url=https://avatars0.githubusercontent.com/u/16845631?v=4; gravatar_id=; url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity; html_url=https://github.com/samvaity; followers_url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity/followers; following_url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity/following{/other_user}; gists_url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity/gists{/gist_id}; starred_url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity/starred{/owner}{/repo}; subscriptions_url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity/subscriptions; organizations_url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity/orgs; repos_url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity/repos; events_url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity/events{/privacy}; received_events_url=https://api.github.com/users/samvaity/received_events; type=User; site_admin=False}
body:
This PR adds a layer over autorest-generated models.

KeyAttributes exposes a key's common attributes but not its jsonWebKey (key/key_material). Most client methods return this.
Key is KeyAttributes plus a jsonWebKey
DeletedKey is KeyAttributes plus deletion/recovery/purge information

Closes #4631 

TODO's left:
`wrap_key`, `unwrap_key`, `import_key`.

body:
Hi there, PM from Azure Pipelines here. We've recently added `pypy2` and `pypy3` as valid targets for the `UsePythonVersion` task. You no longer have to special-case PyPy.

When I tested this on my fork, the Build job fails in exactly the same way with/without my changes, and the PyPy leg itself succeeds.

body:
Hi @johanste, @lmazuel 

This is the first pass of azure-core for review.
It's missing a couple of items:
- Credentials/authentication (hoping to add this in soon)
- Paging/Polling/serialization are still in msrest for now.

title: Added auto-oauth token refreshing for keyvault
user: @{login=dany74q; id=2129762; node_id=MDQ6VXNlcjIxMjk3NjI=; avatar_url=https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/2129762?v=4; gravatar_id=; url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q; html_url=https://github.com/dany74q; followers_url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q/followers; following_url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q/following{/other_user}; gists_url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q/gists{/gist_id}; starred_url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q/starred{/owner}{/repo}; subscriptions_url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q/subscriptions; organizations_url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q/orgs; repos_url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q/repos; events_url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q/events{/privacy}; received_events_url=https://api.github.com/users/dany74q/received_events; type=User; site_admin=False}
body:
Hey key-vault client maintainers !

We've spotted a behavior where 'long running' key vault client instances were suddenly throwing HTTP 401's, while using valid service principal credentials.

After some tests, we've discovered that the key vault client does not refresh its oauth token automatically, which means that the client instance is only valid for use during the duration of its token.

We propose the following changes in order to add a best effort token refreshing.

Would love to hear your thoughts !
Danny
